Introduction

The incarceral system of the United States is extremely large and plays a key role in our society. Across the country on each day in 2018, there were an average of 737126 total people in jail. This is an increase of 143536 in just 20 years; the average number of people in jail per day in 1998 was 593590. These extremely large values only focus on jailed populations; when prison populations are included, it is clear how disturbingly large the number of people in our incarceral system is.

For this project, I decided to focus on analyzing the racial disparities in jail populations. Though the prison systems are also important to analyze, from looking at the Vera Institue for Justices visual tool for the dataset I used, it appeared that they had more data regarding jailed populations. Additionally, as the Vera Institute of Justice says in this article, Conversations about mass incarceration tend to focus on prison, but local jails admit almost 20 times more people annually. Furthermore, one of the issues with jails are that, as the Vera Institute of Justice writes in this article, the criminal justice system, and jails in particular, are a dumping ground for people with substance abuse and mental health problems. For these reasons, I decided to focus on jailed populations.

I also decided to analyze the racial disparities of jailed populations, primarily focusing on the jail systems disproportionate impact on Black populations. This is not to say that the disparities in this system against other racial minorities are not important, but rather only that the disparate impact on Black populations is glaringly obvious in the data. For example, in 2018, the percentage of the general population ages 15 to 64 that was Black was only 13.5%. In contrast, that same year, the percentage of the jailed population that was Black was 33.6%. This proportion is 2.5 times as that of the general population. Contrastingly, the percentage of the general population ages 15 to 64 in 2018 that was white was 60.3%, white the percentage of the jailed population that was white was only 46.9%. In the pie charts below, you can visually see the makeup of both the general population and the jailed population nationally in 2018.

Note: While pie charts can be difficult to interpret, in this situation, where I wanted to display how the composition of the jailed population differs from the composition of the general population, it was the best visualization I could create. The general population only shows ages 15-64, as this was the data included in the data set.

Comparison over time charts

Variable Comparison Charts

The first scatter plot compares the percentage of people ages 15-64 in a county that are Black to the total jailed population of that county. The second scatter plot is set up similarly, but displays the percentage of people that are white.

These scatter plots and their trend lines show us an important correlation; counties that have a higher percentage of Black people have a higher total jail population, whereas counties that have a higher percentage of white people have a lower total jail population. While the total jail population trends upward as the percentage of Black people in an area increases, the total jail population trends downward as the percentage of white people increases.

Also included in these charts is a color-coding based on their urbanicity. The Vera Institute for Justices Codebook explains how it defines urbanicity. A county is urban if it is the core county with a metropolitan area with a million or more people; suburban counties are those surrounding urban ones. Small/mid represents small and medium sized metropolitan areas, and rural indicates even lower populations.

This knowledge allows us to further analyze the data. For example, it makes sense that urban areas tend to have higher jail populations than rural populations; there are more people in urban areas than in rural areas. This is reflected in the scatter plots.
